Though, it seems like she was in some kind of relationship with the boy‚Äôs father, unless she had a one sided crush and kinda stalked him. Anyhow, the woman seems crazy from the start by offering her place to some random teens to drink and party, then getting their cell numbers, and stalking them and meeting their parents. She wants complete control and to be young again, but we don‚Äôt know why yet. There also seems to be some witchcraft stuff going on, and she‚Äôs hiding it in the upper level. text: This looks great just as a movie in general. I love the premise and I'm so happy there's finally a resurgence of ORIGINAL scripts happening in hollywood again.   In respect to the race conversation happening in these comments, I actually like that for once a black character is not coded as a victim in a movie surrounded by white people, and instead she is the one terrorizing them. It's a cool twist on the usual trope. I don't think this movie is doing anything to make black people look better OR worse, it's just a movie and I think some folks are just finding things to be mad at at this point for likes. This shit actually really bothers me. When activists first took to social media to spread awareness about things genuinely worth being upset about, and cultivated this culture of people being able to speak out against injustice and actually be heard, none of us thought it would devolve into people just calling everything problematic like y'all do now. Y'all don't take no breaks. Damn. It's actually real shit to be mad about, this movie ain't even on the list.

text: I see a few comments about how she shouldn't be a villain because of her race but I am not thinking of it in that way. I grew up during the 80's but it wasn't until the mid to late 90's did I start appreciating good movies. I saw it all, trust me, ALL. I watched a lot of movies with Morris Chestnut, Nia Long, Sanaa Lathan, etc. and the movies were good at the time but there was no depth. The plot tended to be the same, the directors just switched the cast around. I appreciated Set It Off, Dead Presidents, Gridlocked, Training Day, heck I even watched Belly. It was at that time that I realized that the industry kept their movies and the cast in a niche and it was disappointing. I am completely appreciating how black directors, producers, writers and the cast are changing the game. I even saw my Aboriginal people (from Canada) step it up this year at VIFF!

text: I love the trailer, and even though it seems like the other horror trends lately "a Social Thriller", it looks like a different social thriller. This one doesn't appear to be using monsters or creatures to convey its' "deeper meaning" like "Us" and "A Quiet Place" etc. The message in this Social Thriller appears to be regarding drug use and the Opioids epidemic. But this movie is still using elements which differ from traditional horrors like slashers and ghosts killing or stalking teens at random and is relying on ordinary humans as the protagonist and antagonist and also relying on atmosphere, dread, suspense, mild violence and mood.

text: Bad. Quite a shame too, because I had high expectations for this one, considering Blumhouse Productions is responsible for The Purge, Happy Death Day, Get Out, Insidious series and much more. Well, I was wrong. The only good thing was Octavia Spencer herself who was MA. She was phenomenal and practically made the movie her bitch. If it wasn‚Äôt for her, the movie would‚Äôve been extremely uncomfortable to watch. Every time I saw her on the screen, I was engaged, but everybody else were just random actors I didn‚Äôt even know and they sucked. It took like a good hour just to have a realistic build up. Ridiculous. And I thought it was supposed to be scary? It‚Äôs not scary at all. Nothing scary in it. Just predictable cheap jump scares that try so hard to scare you, but fail. The story was falling off too much. There were parts where I was locked in, but then the locked in part stops and it gets really boring all of a sudden. The last 20 minutes was the only good part of the movie. It‚Äôs really hard to believe that this was produced by Blumhouse. Blumhouse? What I just saw was definitely not a Blumhouse movie, because I know that Blumhouse can do a way scarier and better job than that.

text: Highly disappointing! In no way had the peers of Octavia Spencer's (Ma's) character duly justify Ma's "mental illness",  properly. Towards the middle of this film, Ma is met by the father to one of the teens she frequently invites to her house parties, and soon realizes he was her junior high/high school crush. When he exposes her illegal doings, he adds a remark to her that she was always a weirdo, and nothing had changed... The problem with that is there were never any justifications on his behalf to indicate that she was "touched".. Matter of fact; her flashback depicts that she was the scapegoat after her classmates discover she has a crush on a boy in her class. They set her up to believe she was gonna make out with the boy in a janitors closet; only to exploit her, causing shame on her when she realizes the girls in her class set her up to give oral to the nerdy kid in class... So, as far as I can perceive this film; Ma's character was and is the victim of possible racism, only to be forced to believe SHE is the problem, all for the sake of maintaining "political correctness" within the white community! I hope persons of color both young and old, realize this fact, and do not fall victim to irrational labeling of one's character based on how he, or she looks.

What she did was wrong, but, so was how they treated her. They had decades to apologize and try to ask forgiveness and make some sort of amends, but didn't. I understand why she did what she did. If you allow negativity to fester within you, then anybody can become "crazy"! She was even poisoning her own daughter by giving her pet meds and convincing her she was sick and to stay home so she wouldn't possibly be bullied as well. Good movie. Sad in a way.

text: For those who will never watch the movie: Octavia's Sue Ann was the victim of a nasty, emotionally traumatizing prank.  While I am absolutely against bullying of all forms (except maybe cyberbullying), it doesn't justify Sue Ann's actions and decisions in this movie.  Different people may have different perspective, but in my eyes, Sue Ann is a person who was incapable of leaving her past behind her, and moving on.  A lot of people get bullied in school, and/or are the "fly-on-the-wall" introvert who no one notices.  But none of that is an excuse to try and live out a teenage dream that you missed out on.  It's bad enough being a grown-ass adult wanting to party with teenage kids.  Even worse is putting your own child in a cage to "protect" her from living and experiencing both the good and bad of life.  And once you resort to torturing kids for not wanting to party with you, you've gone past the point of no return.   An older person wanting to hang out with a younger group is not inherently bad, but there are a few factors which result in it being a bad idea.  Generation gap, differing viewpoints, different interests, different habits, etc.  As an adult who plays video games, I have to deal with the reality that 1) There will be people in my age group who do not like/play all the video games that I play and have played.  Hell, whatever dudes I hung out with in the recent past, not even my tastes in music EVER aligned with their's.  And younger gamers, forget it.  All they want to play is Fortnite or whatever online multiplayer game will be popular next.  It also doesn't help that I am Indian-American, and that majority of Indians my age do not play video games, and most would think I am "childish" for still playing video games.  So, ultimately, I fit in nowhere, and I'm ok with that.  I get more personal satisfaction from my video games and music, movies, and TV shows, than I could ever get from going to a bar on weekends and wasting my money getting drunk or whatever stupid shit that "normal" people do.
